LD-STORAGE-02A — Owned FAT32 Formatter
What this work item is

LD-STORAGE-02A adds a Legacy Doctor owned FAT32 formatter so FAT32 formatting of large removable media does not depend on:

Windows format size policy

third-party formatter executables

GUI tools

ad-hoc shell commands

This formatter must become part of Legacy Doctor’s Tier-0 storage instrument so the tool can deterministically prepare removable media for legacy and modern devices while emitting auditable receipts.

This is specifically for:

SD / microSD

USB flash devices

removable SSD/HDD media where FAT32 is desired

“express card” style prep workflows

future curated device profiles

Tier-0 contract

The owned FAT32 formatter must:

work offline

run under PS5.1 + StrictMode

be deterministic

require explicit destructive intent

emit append-only receipts

verify what it wrote

never silently mutate the wrong disk

support media larger than 32GB

be standalone first, with optional Archive Recall / Triad integration later

Non-goals for LD-STORAGE-02A

This work item does not yet include:

exFAT owned formatter

NTFS owned formatter

GPT multi-partition authoring

device-specific content loading

premium curated load profiles

Archive Recall packet export

Triad restore execution

filesystem repair beyond formatter verification

full file-level indexing/library ingest

Those remain later WBS items.

Functional specification
Command surface

Legacy Doctor storage surface will gain a new explicit command path.

Recommended command names:

-Cmd plan-format-fat32

-Cmd format-fat32-owned

Alternative if you want to preserve the existing format surface:

-Cmd format -Fs fat32 -Formatter owned

But the cleaner Tier-0 contract is explicit command naming.

Required parameters

For destructive owned FAT32 format:

-RepoRoot

-Cmd format-fat32-owned

target selector:

-DiskNumber <int> or

-DeviceId <string>

-Label <string>

-IUnderstand "ERASE_DISK_<n>"

later:

-ClusterKiB <int>

-AutoElevate

-Plan

-WhatIf

Safety rules

Owned FAT32 format must refuse execution unless all are true:

process is elevated

target resolves to exactly one disk

target is not boot disk

target is not system disk

user passed exact destructive token

disk is removable or explicitly override-gated later

there is a successful preflight plan object

partition table/layout verification succeeds before and after writes

